mapTheme <- function(base_size = 12) {
  theme(
    text = element_text( color = "black"),
    plot.title = element_text(size = 14,colour = "black"),
    plot.subtitle=element_text(face="italic"),
    plot.caption=element_text(hjust=0),
    axis.ticks = element_blank(),
    panel.background = element_blank(),axis.title = element_blank(),
    axis.text = element_blank(),
    axis.title.x = element_blank(),
    axis.title.y = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    panel.border = element_rect(colour = "black", fill=NA, size=2)
  )
}

1. Data wrangling

narcotics <- 
  read.socrata("https://data.cityofchicago.org/Public-Safety/Crimes-2017/d62x-nvdr") %>% 
  filter(Primary.Type == "NARCOTICS") %>%
  mutate(x = gsub("[()]", "", Location)) %>%
  separate(x,into= c("Y","X"), sep=",") %>%
  mutate(X = as.numeric(X),
         Y = as.numeric(Y)) %>% 
  na.omit %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("X", "Y"), crs = 4326, agr = "constant")%>%
  st_transform(102271) %>% 
  distinct()
ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data = chicagoBoundary) +
  geom_sf(data = narcotics, colour="red", size=0.1, show.legend = "point") +
  labs(title= "Narcotics Crime, Chicago - 2017") +
  mapTheme()

In this model, I pick narcotics crimes as the outcome. Unlike other types of crimes, narcotics crimes are not reported by the victims after they have been violated, but by the police. Although different neighborhoods may share the same explicit risk factors, some neighborhoods may have more reported crimes due to the reporting bias of police. In other words, the neighborhoods that police pay more attention to may be reported more, instead of the neighborhoods that have a higher risk of drug crime. Thus, there may be more selection bias in drug crimes. The selection bias may cause one set of errors unique to some neighborhoods and another unique to the other neighborhoods. On the following pages, narcotics crimes are predicted with different models in this assignment, to see whether it can account for the selection bias of the reported drug crimes.

narcotics_net <- 
  narcotics %>% 
  dplyr::select() %>% 
  mutate(countNarcotics = 1) %>% 
  aggregate(., fishnet, sum) %>%
  mutate(countNarcotics = ifelse(is.na(countNarcotics), 0, countNarcotics),
         uniqueID = rownames(.),
         cvID = sample(round(nrow(fishnet) / 24), size=nrow(fishnet), replace = TRUE))

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = narcotics_net, aes(fill = countNarcotics)) +
  scale_fill_viridis() +
  labs(title = "Count of Narcotics for the fishnet") +
  mapTheme()

From the above fishnet map, we can see that narcotics crime is very concentrated. They happen the most in the west part of Chicago, and a few of crimes also happen in south Chicago.

nn_function <- function(measureFrom,measureTo,k) {
  measureFrom_Matrix <-
    as.matrix(measureFrom)
  measureTo_Matrix <-
    as.matrix(measureTo)
  nn <-   
    get.knnx(measureTo, measureFrom, k)$nn.dist
    output <-
      as.data.frame(nn) %>%
      rownames_to_column(var = "thisPoint") %>%
      gather(points, point_distance, V1:ncol(.)) %>%
      arrange(as.numeric(thisPoint)) %>%
      group_by(thisPoint) %>%
      summarize(pointDistance = mean(point_distance)) %>%
      arrange(as.numeric(thisPoint)) %>% 
      dplyr::select(-thisPoint) %>%
      pull()
  
  return(output)  
}

The above four maps show the spatial autocorrelation of drug crimes. The result is very intuitive. Local Morans I is large and significant in places with high drug crime rates is low and insignificant in places with low drug crime rates. This means that drug crimes cluster distributed in places with high drug crime rates, and random distributed in places with low drug crime rates.

  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, colour = "#a2d7d8") +
  facet_wrap(~Variable, ncol = 2, scales = "free") +
  labs(title = "Narcotics count as a function of risk/positive factors")

Above shown the scatterplot of the correlation. As the count of abandoned buildings, abandoned cars, garbage cart requests alcohol stores, sanitation requests, rodents and broken street light increases in a grid cell, so does the number of drug crimes. And the closer is these risk factors, the more drug crimes happened. But what wierd is that two positive factors do not show the performance we hoped for. There is no correlation between the count of parks or police stations and drug crime rates. Crimes are also more frequent to happen near police stations and parks. One possible reason is that narcotics crimes basically occurs only in several certain areas, however those factors are in the whole city scale, which reduces the model performance.

5. Poisson Regression

ggplot(final_net, aes(countNarcotics)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1) +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Narcotics Crimes by Grid Cell")

Above shown the distribution of count of drug crimes in each grid cells. 65% of grid cells have at least 1 drug crime, which would render most areas as having a high probability. Also, we can find that this histogram looks similar to the simulated Poisson distribution, instead of OLSs normal distribution or logistic S curve. Thus, we choose Poisson regression to make the prediction.

5.1 Accuracy & Generalzability

reg.vars <- c("Abandoned_Buildings", "Abandoned_Cars.nn", "Graffiti.nn", 
              "Liquor_Retail.nn", "Street_Lights_Out", "Sanitation", "loopDistance", "Garbagecarts", "Policestation.nn","Rodent.nn","Park.nn")

reg.ss.vars <- c("Abandoned_Buildings", "Abandoned_Cars.nn", "Graffiti.nn", 
              "Liquor_Retail.nn", "Street_Lights_Out", "Sanitation", "loopDistance", "Garbagecarts", "Policestation.nn","Rodent.nn","Park.nn",

crossValidate <- function(dataset, id, dependentVariable, indVariables) {

allPredictions <- data.frame()
cvID_list <- unique(dataset[[id]])

for (i in cvID_list) {

  thisFold <- i
  cat("This hold out fold is", thisFold, "\n")

  fold.train <- filter(dataset, dataset[[id]] != thisFold) %>% as.data.frame() %>% 
                dplyr::select(id, geometry, indVariables, dependentVariable)
  fold.test  <- filter(dataset, dataset[[id]] == thisFold) %>% as.data.frame() %>% 
                dplyr::select(id, geometry, indVariables, dependentVariable)
  
  regression <-
    glm(countNarcotics ~ ., family = "poisson", 
      data = fold.train %>% 
      dplyr::select(-geometry, -id))
  
  thisPrediction <- 
    mutate(fold.test, Prediction = predict(regression, fold.test, type = "response"))
    
  allPredictions <-
    rbind(allPredictions, thisPrediction)
    
  }
  return(st_sf(allPredictions))
}

reg.cv <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "cvID",
  dependentVariable = "countNarcotics",
  indVariables = reg.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = cvID, countNarcotics, Prediction, geometry)

reg.ss.cv <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "cvID",
  dependentVariable = "countNarcotics",
  indVariables = reg.ss.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = cvID, countNarcotics, Prediction, geometry)
  
reg.spatialCV <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "name",
  dependentVariable = "countNarcotics",
  indVariables = reg.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = name, countNarcotics, Prediction, geometry)

reg.ss.spatialCV <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "name",
  dependentVariable = "countNarcotics",
  indVariables = reg.ss.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = name, countNarcotics, Prediction, geometry)

reg.summary <- 
  rbind(
    mutate(reg.cv,           Error = countNarcotics - Prediction,
                             Regression = "Random k-fold CV: Just Risk Factors"),
                             
    mutate(reg.ss.cv,        Error = countNarcotics - Prediction,
                             Regression = "Random k-fold CV: Spatial Structure"),
    
    mutate(reg.spatialCV,    Error = countNarcotics - Prediction,
                             Regression = "Spatial LOGO-CV: Just Risk Factors"),
                             
    mutate(reg.ss.spatialCV, Error = countNarcotics - Prediction,
                             Regression = "Spatial LOGO-CV: Spatial Structure")) %>%
    st_sf() 
grid.arrange(
  reg.summary %>%
    ggplot() +
      geom_sf(aes(fill = Prediction)) +
      facet_wrap(~Regression) +
      scale_fill_viridis() +
      labs(title = "Predicted Narcotics by Regression") +
      mapTheme() + theme(legend.position="bottom"),

  filter(reg.summary, Regression == "Random k-fold CV: Just Risk Factors") %>%
    ggplot() +
      geom_sf(aes(fill = countNarcotics)) +
      scale_fill_viridis() +
      labs(title = "Observed Narcotics\n") +
      mapTheme() + theme(legend.position="bottom"), ncol = 2)

Above shown several maps of model prediction result by random k-fold and spatial cross-validation. Comparing it with the right observed map, we can see that models with spatial structure are more accurate than models with only the risk factors which under-predict the west part and over-predict the south part. Besides, random CV model with spatiareal structure performance better than Spatial LOGO-CV model with spatial structure, for the latter model over-predict the south part.

filter(reg.summary, Regression == "Spatial LOGO-CV: Just Risk Factors" | 
         Regression == "Spatial LOGO-CV: Spatial Structure"|
         Regression == "Random k-fold CV: Just Risk Factors"|
         Regression == "Random k-fold CV: Spatial Structure") %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_sf(aes(fill = Error)) +
    facet_wrap(~Regression) +
    scale_fill_viridis() +
    labs(title = "Narcotics crimes errors by Regression") +
    mapTheme()

The error maps prove the interpretation above. The regression with spatial features are more accurate, and Spatial LOGO-CV is also more accurate than Random k-fold CV. In all four models, the west part is under-predicted and the south part is over-predicted. Errors in other places are almost zero.

st_set_geometry(reg.summary, NULL) %>%
  group_by(Regression) %>%

MAE by regression
Regression MAE SD_MAE

Random k-fold CV: Spatial Structure 2.52 5.49

Above shown the table of MAE and standard MAE of different models. The interpretation is that these models error by roughly 2.5 narcotics crimes, on an absolute basis, on average. For context, the average drug crimes per grid cell is 3.776, which means that the average error is over 50%. Another very important information from this reconfirms that prediction models with spatial structural are much more accurate and more generalizable. Spatial structural features improve performance when predicting the hotspots.

#Select the fields we need
  dplyr::select(label, Risk_Category, narcCount)

Above shows two maps that comparing two different models generating risk categories. We can see how they describe the distribution of drug crimes. A strongly fit model should show that the highest risk category is uniquely targeted to places with a high density of burglary point. Although we have already chosen a relatively small 1000 foot search radius for the kernel density, the risk factor regression model still targets to a high density much better. For example, the upper kernel looks like a circle, but drug crimes distribute like a U shape, which successfully explained by the regression model.

rbind(narc_KDE_sf, narc_risk_sf) %>%
  st_set_geometry(NULL) %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -label, -Risk_Category) %>%
  group_by(label, Risk_Category) %>%
  summarize(countNarcotics = sum(Value)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  group_by(label) %>%
  mutate(Rate_of_test_set_crimes = countNarcotics / sum(countNarcotics)) %>%
    ggplot(aes(Risk_Category,Rate_of_test_set_crimes)) +
      geom_bar(aes(fill=label), position="dodge", stat="identity") +
      scale_fill_viridis(discrete = TRUE)

Above shown the chance of observed drug crimes happening in the diffent risk category grid cells. We can see that, in both models, the higher is the risk category, the higher is the rate of the crime. This is great becuase it can help police to locate crime more accurately. Besides, we can see that the risk predictions capture a greater share of observed drug crime events in the highest risk category relative to the kernel density.

7. Conclusion

In this assignment, a geospatial risk prediction model was developed to predict narcotics crimes, for narcotics crimes are reported with more bias compared to other crimes. Although we can see from the result that this new model performs better than the traditional kernel density model, it has some fatal flaws, so that I would not recommend my algorithm be put into production.

The first drawback is that this model lack of generalizability across racial contexts. It may overpredict drug crime rates in Majority Non-White neighborhoods and underpredict drug crime rates of Majority White neighborhoods. This will cause huge trouble when put it into production, because it may lead to over-policing in majority non-white neighborhoods and ignore drug crimes in majority-white neighborhoods. The second reason is that this model has a large error, which is over 50%. Narcotics crimes are highly clustered distributed, with two high crime density centers. Although we can use spatial features to reduce part of the influence, the mean absolute error is still too large to be accepted.
